    {
      "id": "e0445eba5257a94ecd393820920d423fa4c2ddb8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2014-10-01 17:52:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAlexey, I don’t think there is a problem here. The ordering of request_out_callback and reply_in_callback shouldn’t matter. If we get reply_in_callback before request_out_callback then we know that the RPC was delivered and processed within the RPC timeout. We just need to wait for LNET to release its reference on the outgoing buffer.\n\nIdeally we shouldn’t have to wait long for the request_out_callback, and most of the time it will happen very quickly (and before reply_in_callback). But I don’t think any of the LNDs can *guarantee* that request_out_callback will occur before reply_in_callback. That’s just the nature of asynchronous events.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "065fe562f5bad7ddfb6e534c1620ce55167894e2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 136,
        "name": "Alexey Lyashkov",
        "email": "alexey.lyashkov@hpe.com",
        "username": "shadow"
      },
      "date": "2014-10-01 18:05:02.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nChris,\n\ncounting a timeout from a querying to send as now, isn't good idea in general. We can't separate - request isn't send or timeout in network. Yes, it's currently affects a debug output, but it's just now.\n\n        DEBUG_REQ(req->rq_fake ? D_INFO : D_WARNING, req, \"Request \"\n                  \" sent has %s: [sent \"CFS_DURATION_T\"/\"\n                  \"real \"CFS_DURATION_T\"]\",\n                  req->rq_net_err ? \"failed due to network error\" :\n                     ((req->rq_real_sent == 0 ||\n                       cfs_time_before(req->rq_real_sent, req->rq_sent) ||\n                       cfs_time_aftereq(req->rq_real_sent, req->rq_deadline)) ?\n                      \"timed out for sent delay\" : \"timed out for slow reply\"),\n                  req->rq_sent, req->rq_real_sent);\n\nso you will see message a \"time out for sent delay\" instead of \"timed out for slow reply\" it's may broke investigation as make wrong assumption request never send.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "7d30e4f8c01044a2c8243c39e517770a99744cd6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2014-10-01 18:24:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI agree it can result in that message being a little misleading, but how is that a \"-1\" on this patch? We need to ensure that things don't break if the reply_in_callback occurs before the request_out_callback or we need to ensure that this won't ever happen. IMHO, even if we want to guarantee that the request_out will always come before the reply_in then, in the meantime, it would be prudent to land this fix.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
